I understand (having read the linked issue), that you want to raise the visibility of sc-im to attract developers. If you think having a neovim interface to sci-im would do so, I encourage you to implement a lua based plugin, and then advertise it to show people the exciting features that only sci-im.nvim (name free for use) can achieve. Even if you were to bundle sci-vim with neovim, this is (practically speaking) how such an integration would likely take place, which means a lua based plugin will be functionally equivalent.

Bundling another C library as part of nvim (sci-im is ~1/2 the size of luajit) doesn't achieve much other than one less dependency for users to install should they want sci-im. I don't speak for anyone, but I personally have no use for this (I would use a programmatic interface via DataFrames.jl or pandas to work with tabular data), and would not be incentivized to contribute to sci-im development if it were bundled with software I actively contribute to.

@bfredl it doesn't look like it, seems pretty tightly coupled to ncurses
